name: OBCI_0000001
label: ['biomarker']
annotations: Annotation #1: Molecular, histologic, radiographic, or physiologic characteristics are types of biomarkers. A biomarker is not an assessment of how an individual feels, functions, or survives.

name: OBCI_0000002
label: ['diagnostic biomarker']
annotations: Annotation #1: For a perfect diagnostic biomarker test, all patients with the disease or disease subset would be detected (100% sensitivity, i.e., the fraction of people with disease who test positive) and no patients without the disease would be diagnosed with the disease (100% specificity, i.e., the fraction of people without the disease who test negative). In practice no biomarker test has perfect clinical and analytical sensitivity and specificity. [NCBI:books/NBK402285]
column9: Annotation #2: Per CIVic, such biomarkers can help a clinician diagnose or exclude a particular disease.

name: OBCI_0000005
label: ['predictive biomarker']
annotations: Annotation #1: Per CIVic, such biomarkers help predict drug sensitivity or therapeutic response and are valuable in deciding further treatments. Predictive evidence items often explain mechanisms of drug resistance.

name: OBCI_0000006
label: ['prognostic biomarker']
annotations: Annotation #1: Per CIVic, such biomarkers are those that predict survival outcome.

name: OBCI_0000008
label: ['susceptibility/risk biomarker']
annotations: Annotation #1: Per CIVic, such biomarkers are those that indicate an increased likelihood of developing a particular disease.
